Additional analysis show that models trained with the albumin ratio (and NAs records dropped) : a/ perform worse , b/ the albumin ratio is not among the variable selected when an L1-norm is used.

Thus we do not include the albumin ratio in the rest of this analysis.

3 Analysis

3.1 Ordinal regression backward method

glmnetcr model:

  • logistic regression
  • backward or forward flavour : bckwd => P(y=k | y<=k , X)
  • common beta slope for all levels
  • one alpha per level-1
#https:/cran.r-project.org/web/packages/glmnetcr/vignettes/glmnetcr.pdf


# add severity index to table to prevent problems with order
sorted_labels <- paste(sort(as.integer(levels(as.factor(metadata$severity_score)))))

top.prots <- top.prots%>%
  left_join(dplyr::select(metadata, StudyID, severity_score))%>%
  relocate(severity_score, .after = StudyID)%>%
  mutate(severity_score=factor(severity_score , levels = sorted_labels, ordered=TRUE))

y <- top.prots$severity_score

x <- top.prots%>%
  column_to_rownames(var = "StudyID")%>%
  dplyr::select(-severity_score)

fit <- glmnetcr(x, y, method = "backward")
print(fit)

diagnostic plot to find the best lambda (strength of regularization)

plot(fit, xvar = "step", type = "bic")

4 Simple linear regression

In order to complement the analysis with the ordinal regression model, we will perform an analysis with the, simpler, linear regression, but still with some regularization and also with cross-validation for model selection.

note to self: Contrary to the previous case, this model is not, a priori, appropriate for our data, so we will have to check the models assumptions before we can make our conclusion.

# trying simple linear model

X=x

numericY = as.numeric(as.character(y))

linear model with L1 norm (alpha=1) and , 10-fold cross-validation (nfolds=10)

set.seed(36)
nFolds <- 10
foldid <- sample(rep(seq(nFolds), length.out = nrow(X)))
cvfit <- cv.glmnet(as.matrix(X), 
                   numericY , 
                   alpha=1, nfolds = nFolds, foldid = foldid)

plot(cvfit)

* x-axis : strength of regularization * y=axis : Mean squared Error : fitting metric we want to minimize

The error bars around the MSE in that zone are pleasantly small.

the leftmost line is the value of λ that gives minimum mean cross-validated error, while the rightmost one is the value of λ that gives the most regularized model such that the cross-validated error is within one standard error of the minimum.

cvfit$lambda.min
## [1] 0.1702827

It seems a minimum is obtained for lambda ~0.14.

Now, let’s grab the best model and see if it is appropriate

ypred = predict(cvfit, newx = as.matrix(x), s = "lambda.min")

resid = ypred - numericY

par(mfrow=c(2,2))

## checking for gross heteroskedascticity
plot(ypred , resid)
abline(h=0,col='red')

# visualizing  residuals distribution
hist(resid, breaks= seq(-3,3,by=0.25))

# checking normality of residuals
qqnorm(resid)
qqline(resid)

print(summary(resid))
##    lambda.min      
##  Min.   :-2.97762  
##  1st Qu.:-0.74077  
##  Median : 0.09323  
##  Mean   : 0.00000  
##  3rd Qu.: 0.78151  
##  Max.   : 2.04386

The residuals seem to follow a something close to a normal distribution centered on 0 and there is no sign of heteroskedascticity, however there may be a sort of skew (over predict low scores, under predict small scores)…

This is correct, we can actually interpret these results!

plot(ypred, numericY , xlab='model prediction' , ylab='original data')
lines(c(0,10),c(0,10),col='red')

Rsq = cor( ypred , numericY  )**2


RMSE = sqrt( mean( (ypred - numericY)**2 ) )


print('cross validated gaussian linear model ')
## [1] "cross validated gaussian linear model "
print(paste('  R-squared' , Rsq))
## [1] "  R-squared 0.814505587338497"
print(paste('  RMSE' , RMSE))
## [1] "  RMSE 1.20550092444488"

Overall, that looks like an OK fit. The RMSE is still quite high.

4.1.1 Venn diagram

venn.list=list()       
venn.list$"Ordinal\nbackward" <- names(ord_bckwd_param[ 1:(length(ord_bckwd_param)-6) ])
venn.list$"Gaussian lm\nbest RMSE" <- names(nonNull.COEF[2:length(nonNull.COEF)])
venn.list$"Most regularised\ngaussian lm" <- names(nonNull.COEF.1se[2:length(nonNull.COEF.1se)])
venn.list$"Ordinal\nforward" <- names(ord_forwd_param[ 1:(length(ord_forwd_param)-6) ])

# change . in - for all the proteins
venn.list <- lapply(X = venn.list, FUN = function(t) gsub(pattern = ".", replacement = "-", x = t, fixed = TRUE))
# rename OPG
venn.list <- lapply(X = venn.list, FUN = function(t) gsub(pattern = "OPG", replacement = "TNFRSF11B", x = t, fixed = TRUE))

# Generate plot
v <- venn.diagram(venn.list,
                  filename=NULL,
                  
                  # circles color
                  fill = c("#65B3C1", "#284B85", "#F09E39", "#E26247"),
                  alpha = 0.4,
                  
                  # protein labels
                  cex = 0.9,
                  fontface = "bold",
                  fontfamily = "Arial",
                  
                  # circles titles
                  cat.col = c("#65B3C1", "#284B85", "#F09E39", "#E26247"),
                  cat.fontfamily = "Arial",
                  cat.fontface = "bold",
                  cat.cex = 1.2)

# Calculate overlap site
overlaps <- calculate.overlap(venn.list)
overlaps <- overlaps[str_sort(names(overlaps), numeric = TRUE)] # sort base on numeric value

# Apply name to global variable
# Index of venn diagram start at calculate.overlaps + 8. You have to find the index value by yourself for (3,5,6,7,.. venn)
walk2(seq(overlaps) +8, seq(overlaps),  
      function(x,y) {v[[x]]$label <<- paste0(overlaps[[y]], collapse = "\n")})

grid.draw(v)

library(Cairo)
CairoPDF("plots/VennDiagram_top_PlasmaCSFprot_SeverityIndex.pdf", width = 11, height = 9)
grid.draw(v)
dev.off()
